The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, March 26, 2004 				 Bharti foreign currency bonds to raise $100 m
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT				 	 Connecting abroad																								New Delhi, March 25: Bharti Tele-Ventures board today approved a proposal to raise $100 million through the issue of foreign currency convertible bonds (FCCBs).																								The company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange that the board, at its meeting held on Thursday, has decided to raise funds by issue of up to $100 million FCCBs with a greenshoe option of retaining additional $15 million to meet capital expenditure.																								This is subject to the approval of the shareholders of the company and other statutory approvals as may be required. This will be used for expansion projects both in mobility and infotel.																								BTVL has announced its plans to invest Rs 2,000 crore for network expansion. The company already has a tie up with Swedish export credit agency, EKN, and ABN AMRO for funding the import of equipment from Ericsson.																								Akhil Gupta, joint managing director of BTVL, said: The dilution of shareholders equity will occur only if it (FCCB) is converted. Since, the repayment period of the FCCB is five years, it is difficult to predict now. We are yet to finalise the other terms and agreements and premium, the details will be completed soon. The board has cleared it but we also need to take the approval of the shareholders, the details would be ready by then.																								AirTel, the companys mobile business, plans to expand its services to 1000 new towns during 2004-05, out of which 300 towns would be added in the six new circles taking the final count to 2,300 towns in 21 circles.																								Besides the urban areas, the rural sector is set to benefit from AirTels mega expansion drive. AirTel will provide mobile connectivity to 20,000 new villages across the 21 circles during the coming year.																								To cater to the fast-growing mobile base of AirTel in the country, AirTel will be scaling up its capacity to cater to the needs of more than 11 million subscribers by the end of the year. AirTel currently has a subscriber base in excess of 6.2 million.
